{"title_page": "Thomas Kurian", "text_new": "[[Image:Thomas Kurian.jpg|right|thumb|Thomas Kurian at [[Oracle OpenWorld]] in 2010.]]\n'''Thomas Kurian''' is CEO of [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Cloud]], which he joined in January 2019. Prior to that, he was President of  Product Development at [[Oracle Corporation]] from 1996 to 2018.\n\n==Early Life==\nThomas Kurian was born to P.C. Kurian and his wife Molly in 1968 in [[Pampady]] village of [[Kottayam]] district in [[Kerala]], India. Kurian senior was a chemical engineer and the general manager of Graphite India. <ref name=\"thehindu.com\">{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/new-oracle-chiefs-kerala-roots/article6775912.ece?homepage=true | title= New Oracle chief\u2019s Kerala roots | date=11 January 2015 | newspaper=The Hindu | accessdate=30 September 2019 }}</ref>. Thomas Kurian was one among four brothers including his identical twin George Kurian, who is currently CEO of multi-billion dollar company NetApp.\n\nAs their father's career involved moving around India, the twins boarded at the Jesuit-run St Joseph's Boys High School in Bengaluru. Both were accepted to the prestigious [[Indian Institute of Technology Madras]], India. There they both took [[SAT]] tests and sent the results to various colleges, including Princeton University, which liked them so much that both were offered partial scholarship places.<ref>https://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/07/07/george_kurian_reviving_netapps_zing/</ref>. At the age of 17, along with George Kurian,<ref>https://data-economy.com/new-world-pioneers-george-kurian-lays-out-future-vision-of-humankind-built-on-social-consciousness/</ref> he moved to the United States in 1986 . Thomas graduated with a bachelors degree in electrical engineering which he graduated with [[Summa Cum Laude]]. George was in second place.\n\n==McKinsey and Stanford==\nThomas Kurian started his career with [[McKinsey and Company]] as a consultant serving clients in the software, telecommunications, and financial services industries for 6 years <ref name=\"oracle\" /> in London and Brussels.<ref>https://www.gsb.stanford.edu/alumni/contact/alumni-association/about-alumni/thomas-kurian</ref> He also pursured an [[MBA]] from [[Stanford Graduate School of Business]]. He was an Arjay Miller Scholar.{{what}}{{cn}}\n\nAt the time, George was working for Oracle. The year of the big switch came in 1996, when George got hired by McKinsey, and Thomas, by Oracle <ref>\nhttps://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/why-google-clouds-new-ceo-thomas-kurian-quit-oracle-after-22-years/articleshow/66859490.cms?utm_source=contentofinterest&utm_medium=text&utm_campaign=cppst</ref>\n\n==Oracle==\n\nKurian joined Oracle in 1996, initially holding various product management and development positions. His first executive role was as Vice-President of Oracle's e-Business division, driving a number of company-wide initiatives focused on transforming Oracle into an e-Business.\n\nNext Kurian took responsibility for the Oracle Fusion Middleware product family. Under Mr. Kurian\u2019s leadership, that business became the company's fastest-growing business and the industry\u2019s leading middleware product suite.<ref name=\"oracle\" /><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://news.thomasnet.com/companystory/Oracle-Fusion-Middleware-Wins-Two-InfoWorld-Technology-of-the-Year-Awards-811621|title=Oracle Fusion Middleware Wins Two InfoWorld Technology of the Year Awards|publisher=News.thomasnet.com |date=2008-01-15 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gartner.com/technology/media-products/reprints/oracle/article160/article160.html|title=Magic Quadrant for Application Infrastructure for Systematic Application Integration Projects|publisher=Gartner.com |date=2010-10-18 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gartner.com/technology/media-products/reprints/oracle/article163/article163.html|title=Magic Quadrant for Application Infrastructure for Systematic SOA-Style Application Projects|publisher=Gartner.com |date=2010-10-21 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gartner.com/technology/media-products/reprints/oracle/article162/article162.html|title=Magic Quadrant for Shared SOA Interoperability Infrastructure Projects |publisher=Gartner.com|date=2010-10-21 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref>\n\nLater, Mr. Kurian served as a Senior Vice President of Oracle's Server Technologies Division responsible for the development and delivery of [[Oracle Application Server]]s. He played a key role in bringing Oracle 9i application server to market.<ref name=\"bare_url\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://java.sun.com/javaone/sf/2007/sessions/general/bios.jsp |title=2007 JavaOne Conference -General Session Speakers |publisher=Java.sun.com |date=2007-05-08 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref> Application server software became Oracle's fastest-growing business primarily because of his efforts.<ref name=\"bare_url_a\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/news/can-app-servers-revive-oracle/297776|title=Can app servers revive Oracle? |work=CNET News |publisher=News.cnet.com |date=2002-05-22|accessdate=2014-08-08}}</ref>. Kurian served as a member of Oracle\u2019s Executive Committee for 13 years. He led 35,000-people software development team in 32 countries with an R&D budget of $4 billion. Besides, he also helped in the transformation of Oracle\u2019s products with the introduction of leading suite of Cloud Services, led 60 software acquisitions and Oracle\u2019s 45 Cloud data centres.<ref>https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/who-is-thomas-kurian-former-oracle-executive-set-to-take-charge-at-google-cloud/1384839/</ref>\n\nAs the President of Product Development, he oversaw Oracle's 3,000-odd product development efforts. He was responsible for development and delivery of Oracle\u2019s software product portfolio including [[Oracle Database]], [[Oracle Fusion Middleware]], and [[Enterprise resource planning|ERP]], [[Customer relationship management|CRM]], and [[supply chain management]] applications.\n<ref name=\"oracle\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oracle.com/us/corporate/press/Executives/016380.htm |title=Thomas Kurian - Executive Biography |publisher=Oracle.com |date=2010-09-07 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=1345961&ticker=ORCL:US |title=Thomas Kurian: Executive Profile & Biography - Businessweek |publisher=Investing.businessweek.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.forbes.com/profile/kurian-thomas/145799 |title=Kurian Thomas profile |publisher=People.forbes.com |date=2009-08-21 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=E. Abraham Mathew and Srinivas R |url=http://www.ciol.com/News/Interviews/For-Oracle,-every-revolution-is-an-evolution/150007/0/ |title=For Oracle every revolution is an evolution |work=CIOL Interviews |publisher=Ciol.com |date=2011-05-16 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/168477/oracles_software_development_reins_in_new_hands.html |title=Oracle's Software Development Reins in New Hands |work=PCWorld Business Center |publisher=Pcworld.com |date=2009-07-15 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThomas Kurian was the 18th highest-paid man in the US in 2010, according to [[CNN]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2011/fortune/1109/gallery.highest_paid_men.fortune/18.html |title=25 highest-paid men - Thomas Kurian (18) |work=FORTUNE |publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=2011-09-29 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref> He was also the 5th highest-paid tech executive in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horn |first=Leslie |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2396194,00.asp |title=Oracle Execs, Apple's Tim Cook Among Highest-Paid in Tech |publisher=PCMag.com |date=2011-11-10 |accessdate=2012-03-14}}</ref>\n\nOn September 6, 2018, Kurian announced he was taking extended time off from the company.<ref>{{cite news\n| author = Jay Greene\n| title = Top Oracle Software Executive to Take Extended Leave\n| quote =\n| newspaper = The Wall Street Journal\n| date = 2018-09-06\n| pages = \n| url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/top-oracle-software-executive-to-take-extended-leave-1536266283\n| accessdate = 2018-09-08\n}}</ref>. Kurian and [[Larry Ellison]] reportedly had a falling out over the direction of its cloud business <ref>\nhttps://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/why-google-clouds-new-ceo-thomas-kurian-quit-oracle-after-22-years/articleshow/66859490.cms?utm_source=contentofinterest&utm_medium=text&utm_campaign=cppst</ref>\n\nOn September 28, 2018 he resigned from his current designation as president of product development at Oracle.<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/28/oracle-says-kurian-has-resigned-three-weeks-after-taking-time-off.html</ref>\n\n== Google ==\nKurian joined [[Google]]'s Cloud organization in November 2018. On the first year in Google, Kurian focused on selling GSuite applications to enterprise clients. He has reorganized the sales team to align with Sales practices of enterprise clients.<ref>https://techcrunch.com/2020/02/19/thomas-kurian-on-his-first-year-as-google-cloud-ceo/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kurian, Thomas}}\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:Oracle employees]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:McKinsey & Company people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Cleanup bare URLs|date=May 2020}}\n[[Image:Thomas Kurian.jpg|right|thumb|Thomas Kurian at [[Oracle OpenWorld]] in 2010.]]\n'''Thomas Kurian''' is CEO of [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Cloud]], which he joined in January 2019. Prior to that, he was President of  Product Development at [[Oracle Corporation]] from 1996 to 2018.\n\n==Early Life==\nThomas Kurian was born to P.C. Kurian and h